05124nam a22006495i 9780226820170DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20222022ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2021057022  a9780226820170  a(DE-B1597)627326  a(OCoLC)1312158857  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aHF5822b.T38 2022 4aHF5822b.T38 2022 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a659.101/9223/eng/202201031 aTavory, Iddo, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTangled Goods :bThe Practical Life of Pro Bono Advertising /cIddo Tavory, Shelly Ronen, Sonia Prelat. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (208 p.) :b5 halftones, 1 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- t1. Advertising for Good -- t2. Morality in Pro Bono Work -- t3. Good Work; or, The Gift of Unalienated Labor -- t4. The Elephant in the Field: Awards and Recognition -- t5. Curatorial Work: Managers and Organizational Pressures -- t6. Navigating Goods: Boundaries and Bridges -- t7. Evaluating Goods: The Question of Measurement -- t8. Tangled Goods -- tAcknowledgments -- tAppendix: Notes on Method -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA novel investigation of pro bono marketing and the relationship between goods, exploring the complex moral dimensions of philanthropic advertising. The advertising industry may seem like one of the most craven manifestations of capitalism, turning consumption into a virtue. In Tangled Goods, authors Iddo Tavory, Sonia Prelat, and Shelly Ronen consider an important dimension of the advertising industry that appears to depart from the industry’s consumerist foundations: pro bono ad campaigns. Why is an industry known for biting cynicism and cutthroat competition also an industry in which people dedicate time and effort to “doing good”? Interviewing over seventy advertising professionals and managers, the authors trace the complicated meanings of the good in these pro bono projects. Doing something altruistic, they show, often helps employees feel more at ease working for big pharma or corporate banks. Often these projects afford them greater creative leeway than they normally have, as well as the potential for greater recognition. While the authors uncover different motivations behind pro bono work, they are more interested in considering how various notions of the good shift, with different motivations and benefits rising to the surface at different moments. This book sheds new light on how goodness and prestige interact with personal and altruistic motivations to produce value for individuals and institutions and produces a novel theory of the relationship among goods: one of the most fraught questions in sociological theory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAdvertisingxPsychological aspects. 0aAltruism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aAdvertising, Corporate Social Responsibility, Sociology of Culture, Institutional Logics, Pragmatism, Pro Bono.1 aPrelat, Sonia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aRonen, Shelly, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2022 Englishz978311099375208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2022z9783110993738oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete